{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "MethaneOxidationODE",
        "description": "Full time-resolved ODE system for the methane oxidation mechanism in the polluted-continental troposphere (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 6 §6.4 Table 6.1, pp. 219-227). Eighteen-state stiff ODE on the methane oxidation chain CH₄ → CH₃ → CH₃O₂ → CH₃O → HCHO → HCO → CO → (CO₂) plus the supporting NOx/HOx radical chemistry that recycles OH and converts NO ↔ NO₂. The reaction network has 22 reactions: the 17 canonical Table 6.1 reactions covering the Cl-skeleton oxidation chain through HCHO and ozone-formation chemistry via the peroxy + NO channels, plus 5 auxiliary reactions (CO + OH, OH + NO₂ → HNO₃ termination, HO₂ + HO₂ → H₂O₂ termination, NO + O₃ titration, and a zero-order external OH source representing primary OH production from O(¹D) + H₂O that is implicit in the upstream model). Eight termolecular reactions (R2, R6, R13, R14, R17) and the bimolecular cross-reactions have their O₂ and M dependence folded into effective rate constants k6_eff, k13_eff and the explicit k2_0·M·O₂, k14_0·M·O₂, k17_0·M·O₂ products with M_fixed, O2_fixed parameters at fixed STP-tropospheric values (M = 2.5e25 m⁻³, O₂ = 5.25e24 m⁻³). Migrated from GasChem.jl@8c12c048 src/methane_oxidation.jl:213 (`MethaneOxidationODE` @component / @network_component → Catalyst.ode_model). The reaction-network DSL form upstream is converted to explicit ODE equations here because the migration tracker classifies this as `Model` with `variables, parameters, equations` features (not a ReactionSystem-shaped migration — those go to a separate path; see sibling superfast.esm).",
        "tags": [
            "gaschem",
            "methane",
            "tropospheric-chemistry",
            "voc-oxidation",
            "seinfeld-pandis",
            "ode",
            "stiff"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-12T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "GasChem.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-yj3s)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H. and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition, John Wiley & Sons, Hoboken, NJ. Chapter 6 (Chemistry of the Troposphere), §6.4 (Methane Oxidation Cycle), Table 6.1 pp. 219-227 — the canonical 17-reaction Table 6.1 mechanism that this ODE system implements. Rate constants at 298 K, units cm³/molec/s (bimolecular) and cm⁶/molec²/s (termolecular), converted to SI here via ×1e-6 and ×1e-12 respectively."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Jenkin, M. E., Saunders, S. M., Pilling, M. J. (1997). The tropospheric degradation of volatile organic compounds: a protocol for mechanism development. Atmospheric Environment, 31(1), 81-104. Background reference for the auxiliary tropospheric chemistry channels (CO + OH → HO₂ + CO₂, OH + NO₂ → HNO₃, HO₂ + HO₂ → H₂O₂ + O₂, NO + O₃ → NO₂ + O₂) that are not in S&P Table 6.1 but are required to close the tropospheric HOx/NOx budget over a 100-second integration window."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "MethaneOxidationODE": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: GasChem.jl@8c12c048482b515fb8eb2110bf8ab4b4f4e71309:src/methane_oxidation.jl:213\n\nUpstream `MethaneOxidationODE` is an MTK `@component` that internally uses Catalyst.jl's `@network_component` DSL to declare 18 species, 22 reactions, and ~25 parameters, then calls `Catalyst.ode_model(complete(rn); combinatoric_ratelaws = false, name = name)` to convert the reaction network into an ODE system. The migration to `.esm` resolves this two-step construction by emitting the explicit ODE right-hand sides directly — one ODE per species summing the signed-stoichiometry-weighted reaction rates that touch that species. This is bit-equivalent to the Catalyst-generated MTK system because (a) the `combinatoric_ratelaws = false` flag means each reaction rate is just `k · ∏[reactants]` (no `n!` combinatorial factors), and (b) MTK's `complete()` step on the network preserves the user-declared species list exactly, so `unknowns(sys)` returns the same 18 species in the same order.\n\nUpstream test structural-verification invariant (test/test_methane_oxidation.jl `MethaneOxidationODE: Structural Verification` testitem at lines 37-61): asserts `length(unknowns(sys)) == 18` and `length(equations(sys)) == 18` and that the species names CH4, CH3O2, HCHO, OH, HO2, NO, NO2, O3, HNO3, H2O2 appear in the unknowns list — matched here by the 18 entries in `equations` and the 18 `state`-typed entries in `variables` with exactly those species names.\n\nUpstream parameter-list invariant (test/test_methane_oxidation.jl `MethaneOxidationODE: Rate Constants and Parameters` testitem at lines 98-119): checks k1 = 2.45e-12 · exp(-1775/298) · 1e-6 ≈ 6.34e-21 m³/s (Arrhenius pre-factor and activation temperature evaluated at the 298 K reference), k3 = 7.7e-12 · 1e-6 = 7.7e-18 m³/s, k15 = 8.1e-12 · 1e-6 = 8.1e-18 m³/s, k_CO_OH = 2.4e-13 · 1e-6 = 2.4e-19 m³/s, k_OH_NO2 = 1.0e-11 · 1e-6 = 1.0e-17 m³/s, k_HO2_HO2 = 2.9e-12 · 1e-6 = 2.9e-18 m³/s, k_NO_O3 = 1.9e-14 · 1e-6 = 1.9e-20 m³/s, P_OH_ext = 1.0e6 · 1e6 = 1.0e12 m⁻³/s. The migrated `.esm` encodes these as `type: parameter` with the pre-computed Float64 defaults matching the upstream IEEE-754 values exactly (k1 default 6.3437334324972315e-21 is `bitstring(2.45e-12 * exp(-1775/298) * 1.0e-6)` evaluated in Float64 — the upstream Julia parameter default expression evaluates to this exact value at module-load time).\n\nDesign decision: encode all 24 upstream parameters as `type: parameter` (not `type: constant`), mirroring the rig-wide convention for chemistry migrations (chapman.esm encodes its four upstream `@constants` k2_A/k4_A/C_k4/T_ref as `type: parameter`; hox_cycle.esm encodes its eight upstream `@constants` similarly). This lets a downstream consumer override any rate coefficient, photolysis rate, or boundary-condition parameter through the canonical `parameter_overrides` interface for sensitivity studies (e.g. doubled-OH, zero-NOx, half-photolysis, lifetime-at-modified-298K scenarios) — every parameter is an MTK parameter symbol, so the structural distinction between Julia `@constants` (compile-time literals) and `@parameters` (overrideable symbols) is collapsed at the `.esm` schema level.\n\nThe k6_eff and k13_eff parameters retain their upstream pre-folded form: k6_eff = k6 · O₂_fixed = 1.9e-15 · 1e-6 · 5.25e24 = 9975.0 s⁻¹ (the CH₃O + O₂ → HCHO + HO₂ first-order rate at fixed O₂), k13_eff = k13 · O₂_fixed = 5.2e-12 · 1e-6 · 5.25e24 = 2.73e7 s⁻¹ (the HCO + O₂ → CO + HO₂ first-order rate at fixed O₂). The k14_0·M·O₂ and k17_0·M·O₂ products in R14 (H + O₂ + M → HO₂ + M) and R17 (O + O₂ + M → O₃ + M) are kept as explicit triple-products in the ODE RHS (k14_0 · M_fixed · O2_fixed · H, etc.) to preserve the upstream multiplicative-coefficient structure that exposes M_fixed and O2_fixed as overrideable parameters — this is the only way a downstream consumer can probe the M-dependence of the three-body channels at fixed kinetic rate constants (e.g. an altitude sweep at fixed T).\n\nState variable defaults: each of the 18 species carries a `default` value taken from the upstream test's headline scenario (test/test_methane_oxidation.jl `MethaneOxidationODE: Numerical Integration` at lines 444-484): CH4 = 4.5e19 m⁻³ (typical tropospheric ~1800 ppb), CH3O2 = 1e14 m⁻³ (peroxy radical pool), CH3O = 1e10 m⁻³ (trace alkoxy intermediate), CH3OOH = 1e15 m⁻³ (methyl hydroperoxide), HCHO = 1e16 m⁻³ (~0.4 ppb formaldehyde), HCO = 1e10 m⁻³ (formyl trace), CO = 2.5e18 m⁻³ (~100 ppb), H2 = 1.3e19 m⁻³ (~530 ppb molecular hydrogen background), OH = 1e12 m⁻³ (~4e-5 ppt daytime OH), HO2 = 1e14 m⁻³ (~4e-3 ppt HO₂), NO = 2.5e15 m⁻³ (~0.1 ppb NO), NO2 = 2.5e16 m⁻³ (~1 ppb NO₂), O3 = 1e18 m⁻³ (~40 ppb tropospheric ozone), and four species at 0.0 (CH3, H, O, HNO3, H2O2 — initial trace species and accumulating reservoirs). At the all-defaults run these match the upstream test's u0 initial-conditions vector bit-exactly, so the `default_long_term_100s` test reproduces the upstream integration scenario directly without per-species IC overrides.\n\nUnit balance (verified): each of the 18 ODE right-hand sides resolves to m⁻³ s⁻¹ matching the unit of D(species) = d/dt(m⁻³). The bimolecular flux k · A · B has units (m³/s) · (m⁻³) · (m⁻³) = m⁻³/s ✓. The termolecular flux k₀ · M · O₂ · A has units (m⁶/s) · (m⁻³) · (m⁻³) · (m⁻³) = m⁻³/s ✓ (note the leading dimensionality `m⁶/s` of k_0 — `k2_0 ≡ k2_A in 3-body Lindemann low-pressure limit`). Effective first-order rates k_eff · A have units (1/s) · (m⁻³) = m⁻³/s ✓. Photolysis terms j · A have units (1/s) · (m⁻³) = m⁻³/s ✓. The P_OH_ext zero-order source has units m⁻³/s by direct dimensional declaration ✓.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-6): 18-state stiff ODE with widely separated timescales — radical species (OH, HO2, H, CH3, CH3O, HCO) have lifetimes from ~0.001 s (k6_eff = 1e4 s⁻¹ on CH3O) to ~10 s (HO2+NO dominant loss), while CH4 has a multi-year lifetime against OH oxidation (~5 years at 1e12 m⁻³ OH per the `MethaneOxidation: CH4 Lifetime` testitem at test_methane_oxidation.jl:347-374). The 100-second integration window over which the upstream `MethaneOxidationODE: Numerical Integration` test asserts positivity is short on the CH4 timescale (CH4 drops by ~10⁻⁹ relative) but long enough for full radical equilibration. The expected values pinned in the inline tests are LSODA references produced by `earthsci_toolkit.simulation.simulate(rtol=1e-10, atol=1e-12, cse=False)` — the same canonical ESS runner and integrator settings the inline-test gate itself uses — so there is zero cross-integrator drift by construction and the model-level rel=1e-6 (the ESS spec §6.6.4 default tolerance) is applied without broadening, tight enough to catch any real trajectory regression. Test-level override: `initial_conditions_t0` tightens to rel=1e-10 / abs=1e-14 because t=0 carries no integration drift, with abs=1e-14 per-assertion overrides on the five zero-default species CH3, H, O, HNO3, H2O2 where a relative tolerance is undefined at zero.\n\nUpstream test reproduction:\n- `MethaneOxidationODE: Structural Verification` (test_methane_oxidation.jl:37-61): 18 unknowns / 18 equations / required species names — reproduced by the structural shape of the `variables` and `equations` blocks.\n- `MethaneOxidationODE: Rate Constants and Parameters` (test_methane_oxidation.jl:98-119): the 7 explicit parameter-value assertions — reproduced verbatim by the `default` field on each parameter declaration in `variables`.\n- `MethaneOxidationODE: Numerical Integration` (test_methane_oxidation.jl:444-484): 100-second integration with the standard u0 initial-condition vector asserting only `retcode == Success` and `all(x >= -1e-6 * max(abs(vals[1]), 1.0))` positivity — reproduced and tightened by `default_long_term_100s` which pins all 18 species at the three intermediate times t=1, 10, 100 s at rel=1e-6 (the t=0 state is pinned separately by `initial_conditions_t0` at rel=1e-10) so the actual trajectory is the regression target, not just bare positivity.\n- `MethaneOxidationODE: Approximate NOx Conservation` (test_methane_oxidation.jl:489-531): asserts NOx_total = NO + NO2 + HNO3 conserved at rtol=1e-4 over 100s — reproduced by `nox_conservation_100s` pinning the actual NOx_total trajectory (the sum is slowly leaking into HNO3 via the OH+NO₂ termination channel, but conserves to ~1e-5 relative over 100s).\n- `MethaneOxidationODE: CH4 Decreases Monotonically` (test_methane_oxidation.jl:536-575): asserts CH4 monotone non-increasing — reproduced by `default_long_term_100s` pinning CH4 at three times confirming the monotone decrease at the slow OH-driven rate (CH4 drops by ~10⁻⁹ relative over 100s, consistent with the ~5-year tropospheric lifetime).\n- `MethaneOxidationODE: HNO3 and H2O2 Accumulate` (test_methane_oxidation.jl:577-612): asserts HNO3 and H2O2 both positive at t=100s — reproduced by `default_long_term_100s` pinning both as accumulating from 0 to specific positive values.\n\nThe upstream tests do not pin specific trajectory values — they only assert qualitative properties (retcode, positivity, monotonicity, conservation-bound). The migrated `.esm` tests upgrade these to quantitative trajectory pins, which is a tightening — every upstream qualitative assertion is implied by the more-specific pinned value (e.g. `CH4_100 ≈ 4.499999999e19 < 4.5e19 = CH4_0` implies the upstream monotone-decrease assertion). This gives the inline-test gate full regression coverage of the actual numerical trajectory."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-6
            },
            "variables": {
                "k1": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 6.3437334324972315e-21,
                    "description": "CH₄ + OH → CH₃ + H₂O bimolecular rate coefficient at 298 K (Table 6.1 rxn 1, S&P p. 220). Upstream Arrhenius form 2.45e-12 · exp(-1775/T) cm³/molec/s evaluated at T = 298 K, converted to SI via × 1e-6 → m³/s. This is the rate-limiting step of the whole methane oxidation chain (k1 ≈ 6.34e-21 m³/s is ~10⁶ × slower than the typical bimolecular OH-radical reaction rate ~1e-17 m³/s at 298 K)."
                },
                "k3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 7.7e-18,
                    "description": "CH₃O₂ + NO → CH₃O + NO₂ bimolecular rate coefficient at 298 K (Table 6.1 rxn 3, S&P p. 220). The peroxy + NO channel that drives O₃ production via NO → NO₂ conversion. 7.7e-12 cm³/molec/s × 1e-6 → m³/s."
                },
                "k4": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 5.2e-18,
                    "description": "CH₃O₂ + HO₂ → CH₃OOH + O₂ bimolecular rate coefficient at 298 K (Table 6.1 rxn 4, S&P p. 220). The peroxide-forming termination channel that dominates over R3 in low-NOx conditions. 5.2e-12 cm³/molec/s × 1e-6 → m³/s."
                },
                "k5": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 3.5e-19,
                    "description": "CH₃O₂ + CH₃O₂ → products self-reaction rate coefficient at 298 K (Table 6.1 rxn 5, S&P p. 220). 3.5e-13 cm³/molec/s × 1e-6 → m³/s. With combinatoric_ratelaws=false the upstream Catalyst.jl `2CH3O2 → 0` reaction gives a rate k5·[CH3O2]² and removes 2·rate molecules per unit time; this is preserved here in the explicit ODE form as -2·k5·CH3O2² in the D(CH3O2) right-hand side."
                },
                "k7": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 7.043285735348479e-18,
